			      <div type="apparatus">
				        <listApp>
					          <app loc="1">
						            <lem>halaṁpūrasāmina</lem>
						            <rdg source="eiad-bibl:Nilakanta_Sastrib">halaṁpūrasāmine</rdg>
					          </app>
					          <app loc="1">
						            <lem>°ayuvadhinika<unclear>ṁ</unclear>
						            </lem>
						            <rdg source="eiad-bibl:Nilakanta_Sastrib">°ayuvadhinikaṁ</rdg>
						            <note>An editorial note signed by N.L.R. (presumably the
							N. Laksminayarana Rao who contributed to the same
							volume of <bibl>
                        <ptr target="eiad-bibl:zoteroItem_RMUWTUN7"/>
                     </bibl>) suggests that the reading is actually
								<hi rend="italic">°ayuvadhanike</hi>.</note>
					          </app>
					          <app loc="2">
						            <lem>t<unclear>o</unclear>dukasiri</lem>
						            <rdg source="eiad-bibl:Nilakanta_Sastrib">nodukasiri</rdg>
					          </app>
					          <app loc="2">
						            <lem>saṁpadatāṁ</lem>
						            <rdg source="eiad-bibl:Nilakanta_Sastrib">saṁpada<unclear>ttāṁ</unclear>
						            </rdg>
						            <note>Nilakanta Sastri suggests emending <hi rend="italic">saṁpadattaṁ</hi>.</note>
					          </app>
					          <app loc="3">
						            <lem>siriruḻa<unclear>pu</unclear>risadātāsa</lem>
						            <rdg source="eiad-bibl:Nilakanta_Sastrib">siriruḻupūrisadātasa</rdg>
						            <note>The <seg type="graphemic">pu</seg> seems to be the
							result of a correction from an original <seg type="graphemic">da</seg>. We follow <bibl>
								                <ptr target="eiad-bibl:Sircard"/>:
									<citedRange>21 (n. 8)</citedRange>
							              </bibl>, who suggest reading <hi rend="italic">ruḻa</hi> instead of <hi rend="italic">ruḻu</hi>.</note>
					          </app>
					          <app loc="3">
						            <lem>sa<unclear>va</unclear>
						            </lem>
						            <rdg source="eiad-bibl:Nilakanta_Sastrib">sa ta</rdg>
						            <note>The word expected here is <foreign>sava</foreign>
							or <foreign>saṁva</foreign>. The akṣara read as <seg type="graphemic">ta</seg> by Nilakanta Sastri is
							different in shape from all cases of <seg type="graphemic">ta</seg> in the text. It is
							easier to assume a miswritten <seg type="graphemic">va</seg>.</note>
					          </app>
					          <app loc="3">
						            <lem>gipa 1 diva 10 3</lem>
						            <rdg source="eiad-bibl:Nilakanta_Sastrib">gi 8 diva 10
							|||</rdg>
					          </app>
				        </listApp>
