			      <div type="translation" xml:lang="eng">
				<!--<ab>Success! To the Bhagavant, the lord of Halaṁpūra gave this field of Todukasiri for the increase of his lifespan. In the 4th year of Siri-Rudapurisadāta, in the 1st fortnight of summer, on the 13th day.</ab>-->
				        <p>Success! To the Bhagavant, the lord of Halaṁpura, Todukasiri
					gave a field for the increase of his lifespan. In the 4th
					year of Siri-Ruddapurisadatta, in the 1st fortnight of summer,
					on the 13th day.</p>
				        <!--Success! To the Bhagavant! Todukasiri, lord of Halaṁpūra, gave this field for the increase of his lifespan. In the 4th year of Siri-Rudapurisadāta, in the 1st fortnight of summer, on the 13th day.
Or: To the Bhagavant, the lord of Halaṁpūra, Todukāsiri gave …-->
				        <!-- SB email of 20170517 proposes:
  Success! To the Bhagavant, the lord of Halaṁpura,
  the great king Siriruḻupurisadāta, gave the
  Todukasiri Field for the increase of his lifespan.
  Year 4, 1st fortnight of summer, day 13.
i.e., halaṁpūrasāmina as epithet of bhagavate and the
king as donor. If the king is the donor, one might
wonder whether bhagavant‐ halaṁpūrasāmin‐ necessarily
refers to the Buddha (since males as opposed to
females tended to patronize non‐Buddhist deities).
 -->
			      </div>
			      <div type="commentary">
				        <listApp>
					          <app loc="2">
						            <lem>t<unclear>o</unclear>dukasiri <space type="horizontal" quantity="1" unit="character"/> khetaṁ</lem>
						            <note>We assume Todukasiri is the name of the donor and
							is uninflected.</note>
						            <!--<note>If our interpretation of this entire sequence as a compound is correct, then this field named after a person whose name ended in -siri may perhaps be compared to place names such as <foreign>°ukhasirivadhamana</foreign> in some of the Ghantasala inscriptions.</note>-->
					          </app>
				        </listApp>
			      </div>
